    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Mara</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-59589"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-11-30T16:27:17-05:00">Wednesday, November 30, 2016 at 4:27 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Thank you for such a vulnerable, lovely post.  So many people have shared their gratitude and admiration and their words say my feelings more than I can.  What I do have to add though is that I am a child of divorced parents who are still, in many ways, partners.  And my Mom&#8217;s mom also divorced and also stayed friends and family with her ex husband and his eventual new wife.  Seeing and knowing these histories from the perspective of a child is a rare, wonderful, powerful gift.  My parents divorced when I was older, but I never knew my grandparents as a married unit.  The things that were presented to me as truth as a child, and again as a young adult when my parents split, is that love and family are (or, can be) so much bigger than romantic love. That joined history, and a commitment to another person&#8217;s life can take so, so many different forms.  My husband and I knew this when we got married, our vows to one another weren&#8217;t to stay married for life, but to stay married to the idea that we are each-other&#8217;s biggest champions, our safe spaces, our kindest friends, no kidding, no matter what, to the end.  June will grow knowing that you can have bigger expectations of love and what it means to be family and in community than are often modeled for us in our current culture.  What a wonderful thing!  These are big ideas and big feelings and i&#8217;m not sure I&#8217;ve done it justice in a short comment, but I so acknowledge you and admire you for living authentically, and being committed to a life of love and compassion and connection.</p>
    </div>

