  <li id="comment-59631" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Susan</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-59631"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-11-30T19:55:49-05:00">Wednesday, November 30, 2016 at 7:55 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Your books, your thoughts and your efforts have always meant so much to me. The way you write and how it helps with day to day understanding of the complications of life are so valuable. Your sexuality? What does it matter? How often I have thought this since Bruce Jenner became Kaitlyn. </p>
<p>Our society confines everyone to a set life and a set way. How absurd in a country that bases its whole system on personal freedom.</p>
<p>I had a high school boyfriend tell me he is gay and I can&#8217;t tell you how insane that was given the fact that he had professed love for me beyond break up and he married another class mate and had three kids. </p>
<p>Here is my point: if you do it with both sexes you are BI-SEXUAL.  Please feel free to experience that. I have no problem with it, but please don&#8217;t think you are suddenly &#8220;gay.&#8221; </p>
<p>&#8220;Gay&#8221; people do know they are gay. Many people (not me) struggle with the gender roles as evidenced by Kaitlyn. However, the many people are probably BI or brain dead. Luckily, you are BI.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-59631' data-commentid="59631" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-59631" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Susan" aria-label='Reply to Susan'>Reply</a>    </div>
