  <li id="comment-59762" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Laura</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-59762"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-01T15:11:23-05:00">Thursday, December 1, 2016 at 3:11 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly, I&#8217;ve been reading Orangette for ages, and I lived in Seattle for almost a decade and would occasionally see you at the Ballard Market or just around since we lived in the same neighborhood. My dad died right before A Homemade Life came out, and part of grieving was reading about your dad and crying my eyes out. I should have said hi at some point, but anyway — like so many other readers, I feel like you&#8217;re my neighbor, or a friend of a friend. Someone that I know. And I am so proud to read these words. My heart ached for you as I read the first half, and then I swelled with happiness at the second half of them. I&#8217;m only half joking when I say that I feel, as a lesbian, that we&#8217;ve just gotten an amazing addition to my &#8220;team&#8221;—and I know that&#8217;s not quite right, I don&#8217;t like to separate people into teams, when sexuality is fluid and all of them are valid and people are just people—but, well, welcome to the team. We&#8217;re so lucky to have you. Thank you so much for sharing, and I hope the way through leads you to enormous happiness.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-59762' data-commentid="59762" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-59762" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Laura" aria-label='Reply to Laura'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-59763" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://harpsichordian.blogspot.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Liz</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-59763"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-01T15:30:04-05:00">Thursday, December 1, 2016 at 3:30 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>After years of following you here, I was honored to finally meet you last year in Spokane when you read at Aunties Bookstore. And this June my boyfriend and I were visiting Seattle and we went out of our way to finally eat at Delancey. We sat at the bar, trying not to stare at Brandon as he stood at the oven, while I whispered the whole back story to my boyfriend about how the two of you met and how the restaurant came to be. (The pizza was divine, by the way.) You’ve let us in on so much of your life, inspiring all of us to live ours more fully and honestly. On multiple occasions, your words have come at precisely the right time. You capture so well this complicated human experience, and I do hope you’ll keep writing about it as your heart allows. Thank you for writing the things that can make our hearts break and burst at the same time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-59763' data-commentid="59763" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-59763" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Liz" aria-label='Reply to Liz'>Reply</a>    </div>
