  <li id="comment-60121" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">j_____</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60121"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-11T07:54:29-05:00">Sunday, December 11, 2016 at 7:54 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly,</p>
<p>I am a long-time reader and gay man approaching thirty. Our experiences are not identical—though I have some equally complicated struggles behind me—and I would never presume to know precisely what you are dealing with or advise you on how to handle it. However:</p>
<p>I know what you are feeling, and I know, more importantly, the depressive and bewildering emotional tangle you have been living in for months and probably years before that moment of self-assertion and, inevitably, exhaustion in the hospital room. You will carry those emotions with you forever not as a burden but, finally, as a massive and profound victory. You should be proud: proud to have, in coming out, a wider, richer array of experiences in the universe than many people can even imagine; proud to have the courage to see yourself with honesty, in spite of the complications it will create; proud to have behind you—and before you, it seems—a relationship which in its own way was poignantly unexpected and fruitful, which was what it needed to be for as long as it needed to be, which is already adapting and evolving better post-marriage than most life-long marriages, and which, through your daughter, gave you a kind of love, distinct from any other, that you might have never known.</p>
<p>My mother stayed in her poisonous, mildly-abusive marriage for eighteen years, arguably seventeen years and six kids longer than she should have. It is hard not to wish she had found in herself, decades ago, even the teensiest capacity for self-avowal that leads, eventually, to that defiant scream that is Coming Out. Repression is always a countdown, and I cannot help but wish she had “come out” before her world obliterated, her confidence and self-awareness permanently nuked. It is understandable that you would grieve the loss of an image of a certain kind of life. It is understandable that June’s adorably and tragically idyllic image would compound and complicate that grief. But know that in standing a little taller now you have avoided even greater grief later, escaped full emotional obliteration, and somewhere in that is—or will be—peace. </p>
<p>And gratitude. Gratitude for new truer relationships with the same people. Gratitude for a queer uncle and a family with a history of queer advocacy and support (a comfort we sadly have not all had). Gratitude for a platform and for an equally supportive comment section. Gratitude, too, for those who before us have spoken the very same “I am here” in the face of more confusing, more hostile, more dehumanizing odds than we faced and in so doing laid a stone for you and me to step on. </p>
<p>Blah blah blah, all this to say I am /excited/ for you.</p>
    </div>

