  <li id="comment-60337" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Nicole</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60337"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-20T17:48:54-05:00">Tuesday, December 20, 2016 at 5:48 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I feel like my words would be but an echo of all who responded earlier. But I wanted to make sure you knew that there was one more reader, one more person, one more woman who you entirely captivated with your honesty and vulnerability and just your true being, told solely through your writing. It&#8217;s thoroughly weird to feel so intimately connected to someone without even meeting them. But that&#8217;s how I feel with you and that&#8217;s how I feel for you. Thank you a million times over for letting us readers into your life and learning and growing along with you. (My own mother passed away 14 years ago and so I feel a kindred spirit with you.) It is worth more than you could ever know. I visit Seattle often and if I ever get the chance to meet you, you will know by my enthusiastic shrieking Asian noises that cross your path! Thank you for everything your heart has unfolded!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60337' data-commentid="60337" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60337" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Nicole" aria-label='Reply to Nicole'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60339" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Megan</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60339"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-20T18:10:02-05:00">Tuesday, December 20, 2016 at 6:10 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I came across this today, from the much-loved and much-read General Theory of Love by Thomas Lewis:</p>
<p>“A person cannot direct his emotional life in the way he bids his motor system to reach for a cup. He cannot will himself to want the right things, or to love the right person, or to be happy after a disappointment, or even to be happy in happy times. …Emotional life can be influenced, but it cannot be commanded.”</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60339' data-commentid="60339" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60339" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Megan" aria-label='Reply to Megan'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60345" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Caitlin Marshall</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60345"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-20T22:38:05-05:00">Tuesday, December 20, 2016 at 10:38 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Dear Molly, thank you for sharing.  I&#8217;d like to go back to what you talked about at the start of your post, too, when you realized you had to write about the experience of your father&#8217;s death. I picked up A Homemade Life when it came out, not knowing much about your writing and looking for a bit of tra la la to spend time with on lunch break at work.  </p>
<p>I had not long ago lost my brother in law, to brain cancer, and was with him in the moment when he passed away. </p>
<p>So there I was, sitting in the sunshine with my sandwich, and I came to that passage, and I just lost it. But it was in the best way possible: it gave me permission to feel some feelings I didn&#8217;t realize needed feeling.  Great writing can have the capacity to do that, and it is one of the things I most love, and find hope in, about being human.  </p>
<p>Thank you for your strength, grace, and eloquence.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60345' data-commentid="60345" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60345" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Caitlin Marshall" aria-label='Reply to Caitlin Marshall'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60374" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Ash</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60374"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-21T18:36:43-05:00">Wednesday, December 21, 2016 at 6:36 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Dear Molly,</p>
<p>Guess you have heard it a thousand times before this comment is that you are brave. You indeed are. but more than that you are honest. to yourself and to the ones you love so dearly.<br />
Half of our lives we worry about truth hurting our loved ones but its actually the lies that do. And you have done one of the best, brutal yet honest thing. You have said the truth.<br />
It is actually this honesty that prompted a mute reader of your blog to actually pen her thoughts in your comment section.</p>
<p>I believe in this thing more than anything else. &#8220;truth sets you free&#8221;.</p>
<p>Even if you may be on uncertain footing at the moment, at the end of the day you will sleep well.</p>
<p>God bless you.</p>
<p>Warmest regards,<br />
Ash</p>
    </div>

