      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60519"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-28T20:43:41-05:00">Wednesday, December 28, 2016 at 8:43 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hug&#8230;<br />
&#8220;We do not grow absolutely, chronologically. We grow sometimes in one dimension, and not in another; unevenly. We grow partially. We are relative. We are mature in one realm, childish in another. The past, present, and future mingle and pull us backward, forward, or fix us in the present. We are made up of layers, cells, constellations.&#8221; Anais Nin</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60519' data-commentid="60519" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60519" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Fiona" aria-label='Reply to Fiona'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60521" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Amelia</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60521"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-28T21:39:00-05:00">Wednesday, December 28, 2016 at 9:39 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Ah, this being human thing is so very hard.  I&#8217;m still waiting for the day that I figure things out, that I feel grown up, that I know myself.  And the message I keep hearing is that it never really happens.  Humanity has survived for so long by adapting and embracing change.  Thank you for sharing your heart with us, as well as your recipes.  I make the Winning Hearts and Minds cake whenever I need to show love, and your macaroon recipe at the slightest provocation.  Light and love.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60521' data-commentid="60521" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60521" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Amelia" aria-label='Reply to Amelia'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60526" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Abbi</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60526"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-28T22:52:13-05:00">Wednesday, December 28, 2016 at 10:52 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly,</p>
<p>I am late to the game with this, but I had to come to the source once my curiosity was piqued with the fish in your Instagram post today (what a phenomenal gift!). </p>
<p>My husband and I separated when I was eight months pregnant with our son and we were officially divorced in May of the following year; the lilacs were just budding in Northern Michigan and, in the most cliche of cliches, the clouds parted to reveal blue sky as I walked out of the courthouse that day. Almost three years later, I still feel the heaviness you mention when I see photographs of married couples with children. But our son is smart and funny and kind and challenging, and after a few bumps in the road &#8211; with more to arrive later, which we will navigate when the time comes &#8211; we mostly have things sorted out. </p>
<p>A thousand kudos to you for accepting your authentic self, for doing the hard work of wading through change and navigating complicated everythings, and for sharing your story here in this space. So many hugs to you!</p>
<p>An equal thousand kudos go to your readers, too, who have showered you with support. I&#8217;m finding the comments almost as inspiring as your original post!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60526' data-commentid="60526" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60526" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Abbi" aria-label='Reply to Abbi'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-60527" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Deanna Costa</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60527"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-28T22:58:01-05:00">Wednesday, December 28, 2016 at 10:58 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi Molly,  I came to a similar epiphany when I in my early 30s.  I was married with two children with my husband, 2 stepdaughters and and a stepdaughter from a previous relationship.  For me, it all came to light in an actual moment.  The next couple of years where filled with every emotion from depression &amp; doubt to absolute joy and elation.  I am now 56, have been with my wife for 20 years.  She helped me raise my kids and we are grandmothers to 3 (soon to be 5!) grandchildren.  I know this journey of yours will not always be an easy one and being true to yourself can sometimes take a lot of courage, that you will sometimes find hard to muster.  I wish you strength, love and light.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-60527' data-commentid="60527" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-60527" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Deanna Costa" aria-label='Reply to Deanna Costa'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
