      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">laura mason-marshall</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-60785"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-01-08T21:54:50-05:00">Sunday, January 8, 2017 at 9:54 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>&#8220;Having a baby, having her, softened me. It broke me a little. It gave me first-hand knowledge of the fullness of joy and the emptiness of clinical depression. It made me appreciate my body, and femaleness, in a new way. It committed me to becoming the kind of person I want June to know and remember and be proud of. It committed me to being a person I want to parent her. It made me brave.&#8221;  </p>
<p>I have a 16 month old daughter, and I read this post last night, and I keep thinking about your beautiful phrasing regarding the ongoing beautiful struggle of parenting. Yes, this! I want to be the person that I want parenting my child. I want to keep doing my best to be that person every day. You are doing incredible and soul-searching work to be the person you are, a person your daughter will indeed be proud of.  Thanks for this heart-opening post that reached so many of us! What breadth and depth in your love.</p>
    </div>

