  <li id="comment-61092" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.etsy.com/shop/BeelineStudio" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">olive tyrrell</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61092"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-01-18T22:18:13-05:00">Wednesday, January 18, 2017 at 10:18 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I am an old reader of your blog that hasn&#8217;t read in such a long time. I have tears streaming down my face, like many others before me. I am also a woman who didn&#8217;t ever believe she was anything other than straight. I am definitely not a woman who sent my youth in the closet. I had been with men my whole life. I started dating women in my early 30&#8217;s.  I never, and still don&#8217;t believe that I was born gay. I think of it as fluidity as you say. And I am fine with that. I don&#8217;t want to be defined. I don&#8217;t think we have to be. In the beginning of &#8220;switching teams&#8221; it&#8217;s super hard to navigate friendships and the past, and family, and what&#8217;s going on &#8211; it feels secret and weird to come out to all of your straight friends. Now 10 years later, everyone in my life, including me, is fine, happy, and thinks fuck, why do we all (society) have to make sexual preference such a big deal? We all love, we all want the same things no? Happiness, love, fulfillment, laughter, kindness&#8230;..etc etc etc etc &#8211; and honestly one thing that makes me super proud is that before my Mom passed away, a few years before, I came out to her, and to my relief she was just happy to see that I was happy &#8211; none of the crap I thought mattered to her, mattered. She only wanted me to have love.</p>
    </div>

