      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61101"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-01-19T11:06:48-05:00">Thursday, January 19, 2017 at 11:06 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I haven&#8217;t been on-line much these past couple of months (couldn&#8217;t bear to read all the negativity after the election- from both sides- and then couldn&#8217;t bear to think what will happen to this country&#8230;). For some reason I opened your blog again (I used to read it every week) and found this post. As always, you have presented your thoughts in a coherant and gentle way. I particularly admire how  you and Brandon are dealing with co-parenting. June will be better for it. While I have not experienced the feelings you have, I do know how it feels to have your world turned upside down due to things  you have no control over. A little over 2 years ago my 20-something year old informed me that &#8220;he&#8221; was going to begin the process to become a &#8220;she&#8221;. I was floored.. Had never even considered this possibility and knew little about what this meant.. But with the help of a wonderful support group of other parents, I have learned that being who you really are (and know to your soul you are), your authentic self, is the most important thing in life. These days my daughter is happy, beautiful, and more content than I have ever known&#8230; My real regret is that it took her so long to come out &#8211; time spent in anguish over her misplaced identity. My wish to you is that your new discovery about yourself will lead you to even more discoveries as you tease out what feels right to you and what doesn&#8217;t. And while I understand the other comments telling you that you are brave (and they are not wrong)- I think I would instead say that you seem very aware of yourself. But then you always seem to have been more self-aware than most. Be kind to yourself Molly.</p>
    </div>

