  <li id="comment-61403" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://illmakeitmyself.net" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">illmakeitmyself</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61403"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-01-22T20:28:45-05:00">Sunday, January 22, 2017 at 8:28 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>First of all: Welcome to the rainbow club!! </p>
<p>Second, I&#8217;m really glad that you&#8217;re not erasing bisexuals while figuring your preferred label out. I&#8217;m sure you&#8217;ve seen this in the news when celebs get a girlfriend and the media is like &#8220;you can only be lesbians or live in gal pals, bisexuality doesn&#8217;t exist.&#8221; (To quote Robyn Ochs, &#8220;I call myself bisexual because I acknowledge that I have in myself the potential to be attracted – romantically and/or sexually – to people of more than one sex and/or gender, not necessarily at the same time, not necessarily in the same way, and not necessarily to the same degree.&#8221;)</p>
<p>Anyway, I&#8217;m a genderqueer bisexual and my partner and I are thrilled you came out! It means a lot to me to see other food folks out and about.</p>
<p>If there are any bisexual types hanging in the comments, come hang out with us at Seattle Bi Women&#8217;s* Network on Facebook (*cis and trans women attend, as well as some non-binary assigned-female-at-birth types like myself). </p>
<p>Also, Seattle has tons of resources for queer folks of all types, like PFLAG, which is a support group for LGBTQIA folks + their friends and families. There&#8217;s on in Cap Hill and one in Bellevue.</p>
<p>In solidarity and congrats again!</p>
<p>LM</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-61403' data-commentid="61403" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-61403" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to illmakeitmyself" aria-label='Reply to illmakeitmyself'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-61535" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Stephie</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61535"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-01-25T09:17:59-05:00">Wednesday, January 25, 2017 at 9:17 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>You continue to amaze me. I&#8217;ve been reading your words off and on for years, yours is one of the very first blogs I ever found and loved. You always felt so other-worldly to me.  So eloquent with your words and ability to pull me right into your world for those brief moments you share it.</p>
<p> I can&#8217;t say I fully understand what you&#8217;re going through but I think you&#8217;re courageous and so strong to not just talk about it, but to allow yourself to follow your heart.  Too many of us just stay where we are because of fear of the unknown, because it&#8217;s hard to change, because, what if? I wish you strength and courage to follow your needs and pursue those wants because you deserve to be happy. We all do.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-61535' data-commentid="61535" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-61535" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Stephie" aria-label='Reply to Stephie'>Reply</a>    </div>
