  <li id="comment-61823" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://e2bakesbrooklyn.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Liz</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61823"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-02-04T03:22:10-05:00">Saturday, February 4, 2017 at 3:22 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I don&#8217;t know that I&#8217;ve ever commented here before, but I&#8217;ve been a reader (and podcast listener!) for years. I ended a long term relationship about a year ago. My ex, who is ten years older than I, determined that he did not want to have children. I am 31 and I cannot ever remember not wanting to be a mother. We loved each other in this deep, earth-shattering way that I can&#8217;t describe to someone who hasn&#8217;t experienced that sort of love. The sort where even though nobody did anything wrong and nobody drifted out of love, we still had to end it so that we could be who we are. I, the woman who wants children, and he, the man who doesn&#8217;t. We ended it *because* we loved each other. My heart was broken in a way that I didn&#8217;t know it could be&#8211;you&#8217;re right, it was as though someone had died. I moved ten blocks away into the nicest apartment I&#8217;ve ever had. My business boomed. I took the most fun trip to Maine with my three closest girlfriends. And yet, it still took me a year to feel like me. I moved on February 13th of last year (nothing like having your first day of single ladyhood in seven years on Valentine&#8217;s Day). I have now felt &#8220;normal&#8221; for three weeks. In the last year, we have texted when we had something to say, and met up once outside of the laundromat on a Saturday morning to exchange mail. And my heart broke again every time. But now, I don&#8217;t feel like a gust of wind is going to break me. And I don&#8217;t feel like living in the past, even though it was lovely. I feel like being me right now. I don&#8217;t know that I could be happier to be who I am in this moment. I can&#8217;t wait to find out who I become.</p>
<p>Congratulations on who you are and on who you are becoming. I hope you, Brandon, and June have the loveliest lives.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-61823' data-commentid="61823" data-postid="9748" data-belowelement="comment-61823" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Liz" aria-label='Reply to Liz'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-61842" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">KG</cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-61842"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-02-05T03:14:41-05:00">Sunday, February 5, 2017 at 3:14 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I saw something you posted on Instagram a little while ago and was like &#8216;oh boy. I missed a really big post&#8217;. </p>
<p>as someone who had the gentlest realisation at the age of 29 about my sexuality I can relate to this. doing this journey with a husband and child wouldn&#8217;t have been quite so gentle; but I&#8217;m so so glad that you&#8217;re in a community and family that support you through this, especially with your natural talent for resisting change. </p>
<p>I&#8217;m crying a lil bit, but I&#8217;m just so glad you haven&#8217;t lost your best friend even if he&#8217;s not your husband anymore. </p>
<p>I wish you all the best in your continuing journey in a country that is all the sudden far less friendly to people like us.  </p>
<p>and thank you so, so much for writing about it. the more stories that are out there the more we will be able to understand that nothing about humanity is prescribed or fixed in any way. </p>
<p>anyway that was a lot of words. i hope they made sense.</p>
    </div>

