    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.nuu-muu.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Chelle Davidson</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-65961"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-08-09T17:44:43-04:00">Wednesday, August 9, 2017 at 5:44 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi Molly.  I haven&#8217;t visited your blog in a really long time, but I loved your books and I live in Bellingham and have had a sweet friendship with Jessica and Mataio at Ciao Thyme for a long time.  I read this post and am deeply happy and sad for you.<br />
I wanted to share what I have learned about love and divorce and parenting this past 24 years of my daughter&#8217;s life.  Her father and I divorced when she was three 1/2.  I loved him dearly, but not as a wife.  24 years later, we are still best friends and our respective partners&#8211;his wife and my husband&#8211;have formed an unbreakable family.  We actually refer to ourselves as the Lucky Charms as our initials spell out CHARM.  We have raised our only daughter together.  His wife and I co-own a little dress company together.  We go on vacations, the five of us and genuinely love each other.<br />
Our daughter is about to embark on her own adventure as she heads to Dublin, Ireland for Graduate school at Trinity College.  We all plan to head over there and have an Irish Christmas.<br />
It works and you and Brandon will make it work. It sounds like you already are.  </p>
<p>Best,</p>
    </div>

