  <li id="comment-68396" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.rockyroadlife.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Katie Burford</a></cite></div>
      <a href="http://orangette.net/2016/11/november-30/#comment-68396"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2018-01-07T17:47:44-05:00">Sunday, January 7, 2018 at 5:47 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Molly, to say I can relate would be wildly understating it. I&#8217;m a mother, whose marriage went through a major upheaval resulting from starting a food-related business (I was a journalist who decided she absolutely HAD to open an artisan ice cream shop), who ended up divorcing but staying very close to her ex, AND who ended up coming out. Crazy. I also grew up in Oklahoma, where I literally did not know a single gay person. For me the process of living a true and honest life started 5 years ago with my recovery from alcoholism. The journey was brutal, but now I know I am loved as the real me. Something that is kind of funny is that I first came across your book Delancey as I was starting to write about my own experiences. I started following you on social media but always felt intimidated by your picture-perfect life. I was envious that your marriage had survived the ordeal of starting a business while mine had failed. Then I saw this. So brave. Thank you so much for sharing your struggle. It makes the beauty you create all the more beautiful. From now on, you can count me as an avid reader.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
